---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is FPS?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "First-Person Shooter, a genre focusing on gun and other weapon-based combat in a first-person perspective."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is MOBA?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Multiplayer Online Battle Arena, where two teams compete against each other on a predefined map."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is MMO?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Massively Multiplayer Online game, supporting large numbers of players simultaneously over the internet."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is Competitive Gaming?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Ranked or professional play where skill, strategy, and ranking systems like ELO or MMR are paramount."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is Esports?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Organized, multiplayer video game competitions, often between professional players."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<SiteLayout
  site="leeroyjenkins"
  title="Gaming Jargon Dictionary: 200 Terms Explained"
  description="The ultimate gaming jargon dictionary explaining 200 essential terms including FPS, MOBA, MMO, competitive, and streaming jargon."
  canonical="https://leeroyjenkins.quest/gaming-jargon-dictionary"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Gaming Jargon Dictionary: 200 Terms Explained</h1>
      <p>The ultimate gaming jargon dictionary explaining 200 essential terms including FPS, MOBA, MMO, competitive, and streaming jargon.</p>
    </div>


<h2>The Complete Glossary</h2>
<p>Welcome to the ultimate gaming jargon dictionary. Whether you are navigating the complex worlds of MMOs, coordinating strikes in FPS games, or just trying to understand Twitch chat, this highly curated glossary of over 200 essential terms has you covered.</p>

    <div class="card">
        <h3>ADC (Attack Damage Carry)</h3>
        <p>A role typically played in the bottom lane. ADCs deal consistent, high physical damage primarily through basic attacks, becoming extremely powerful in the late game but requiring protection due to their low health.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>ADS (Aim Down Sights)</h3>
        <p>The action of looking through a weapon's optics, scope, or iron sights for increased accuracy and zoom, often at the cost of movement speed or peripheral vision.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Aggro</h3>
        <p>Short for aggression. It is the underlying AI mechanic that dictates which specific player an enemy will target and attack. Tanks utilize 'taunt' abilities to deliberately draw aggro, protecting their vulnerable teammates from taking damage.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>AIO (All-In-One Cooler)</h3>
        <p>A closed-loop liquid cooling system used primarily to cool the CPU. It consists of a pump block attached to the processor, connected via tubes to a radiator equipped with fans, offering excellent thermal performance and aesthetics.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Airflow</h3>
        <p>The critical movement of cool air into the PC case and hot air out, managed by case fans. Proper airflow is absolutely essential to maintain low temperatures and prevent thermal throttling of the CPU and GPU.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Alerts</h3>
        <p>On-screen graphics and sound effects that trigger automatically during a stream to acknowledge viewer actions, such as someone following the channel, subscribing, or making a financial donation.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Analyst desk</h3>
        <p>A panel of highly knowledgeable former professionals and experts who appear before and after matches to break down the draft, utilize statistics to analyze team performance, and dissect the crucial turning points of the game.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Anchor</h3>
        <p>A defensive player whose job is to lock down a specific bomb site or area entirely on their own, delaying the enemy team while their teammates rotate to assist.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Asset flip</h3>
        <p>An extremely low-quality, exploitative game hastily assembled using pre-made 3D models and code purchased directly from unity or unreal asset stores, completely lacking original gameplay or art, designed solely to make a quick profit on digital storefronts.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Backseating</h3>
        <p>When a viewer unsolicitedly tells the streamer exactly what to do, solves puzzles for them, or constantly offers strategic advice, which is generally considered annoying and is banned in many channels.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Ban</h3>
        <p>A permanent restriction that entirely blocks a user from participating in a channel's chat, reserved for severe or repeated violations of the community guidelines.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Bandwidth</h3>
        <p>The maximum amount of data your internet connection can download or upload per second. While high bandwidth is necessary for downloading huge game files quickly, online gaming itself actually requires very little bandwidth; latency is far more important.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Bit</h3>
        <p>A virtual good or currency purchased by viewers on Twitch and used to 'Cheer' in a streamer's chat. Streamers receive a portion of the revenue for every Bit cheered in their channel.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Bitrate</h3>
        <p>The amount of data processed per second during a live stream, measured in kilobits per second (kbps). A higher bitrate results in a sharper, clearer video, but requires a faster, more stable internet upload speed from the streamer.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Bo3 / Bo5 (Best of X)</h3>
        <p>The standard match format indicating the maximum possible number of games played in a series. In a Best of 3, the first team to win two games secures the overall match victory, allowing for map vetoes and strategic adjustments.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Bootcamp</h3>
        <p>A dedicated period of intense, highly focused practice. An entire team will travel to gather in a single location or facility, often in a different region with stronger competition, to train ruthlessly for weeks prior to a major world championship.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Bottleneck</h3>
        <p>A severe performance limitation that occurs when one critical component (e.g., an outdated CPU) is significantly slower than the rest of the system (e.g., a brand new, high-end GPU), preventing the faster components from operating at their full potential.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Bracket</h3>
        <p>The visual, tree-like tournament structure that dictates exactly which teams face each other. Tournaments commonly use either Single Elimination (one loss and you are out) or Double Elimination (teams drop to a lower bracket after one loss).</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Buff</h3>
        <p>A balance change implemented by the developers in a patch that increases the power, stats, or utility of a character, item, or strategy that was previously underperforming or considered too weak.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Bufferbloat</h3>
        <p>A phenomenon where a router buffers too much data when the network is congested, causing massive spikes in latency. This often happens when someone else in the house is streaming 4K video or downloading a large file while you are gaming.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Bullet sponge</h3>
        <p>A highly derogatory term for a remarkably uninspired boss or enemy type that poses absolutely no strategic threat, but simply possesses a massive, inflated health pool, requiring the player to monotonously shoot them for an extended period of time to defeat them.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Bunny hopping (B-hop)</h3>
        <p>An advanced movement technique that involves chaining perfectly timed jumps while turning in mid-air to gain or maintain momentum, often allowing a player to move faster than the game's standard running speed.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Buyout</h3>
        <p>The incredibly massive, often multi-million dollar fee that an esports organization must pay to legally acquire a highly skilled star player who is currently locked into a long-term, legally binding contract with a rival organization.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Camp</h3>
        <p>Remaining in a single, advantageous, and often hidden position for an extended period to ambush enemies as they walk by, rather than actively roaming the map.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Capture card</h3>
        <p>A physical hardware device used to capture the audio and video signal from a gaming console (like a PS5 or Switch) or a dual-PC setup, sending it to the streaming computer for broadcast via OBS.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Carry</h3>
        <p>A player or specific character role whose performance is the primary reason their team wins the match. Carrying usually implies dealing the vast majority of the team's damage or making game-winning plays.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Caster</h3>
        <p>The on-screen talent who provide live, exciting commentary during esports matches. Play-by-play casters bring massive hype during intense moments, while color commentators break down the deep, underlying strategies and decisions in real-time.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>CC (Crowd Control)</h3>
        <p>Any ability or status effect that limits the movement or actions of an opponent. Common forms include stuns, slows, roots, silences, and knock-ups.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Chat</h3>
        <p>The live text communication window alongside the video player. Managing, interacting with, and moderating chat is one of the most critical and challenging aspects of being a successful live streamer.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Cheese strategy</h3>
        <p>An highly unconventional, unpredictable, and often risky strategy that relies entirely on catching the opponent completely off guard. If scouted or expected, a cheese strategy usually fails spectacularly.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Client-side</h3>
        <p>Calculations or actions that are handled entirely by the player's own computer (the client) rather than the main server. While responsive, relying heavily on client-side authority makes a game highly vulnerable to hackers and cheats.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Clutch</h3>
        <p>Successfully winning a round or match when you are the last surviving member of your team against multiple remaining opponents.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Clutch</h3>
        <p>The incredibly tense scenario where a single remaining player successfully manages to win a round against seemingly impossible odds, often eliminating multiple opponents entirely on their own under massive pressure.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Coach</h3>
        <p>The vital mastermind behind the team who handles macro strategy, rigorous VOD reviews, drafting phases, and emotional support. A great coach ensures the players focus entirely on their mechanics while executing a cohesive, highly practiced game plan.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>CPU (Central Processing Unit)</h3>
        <p>The processor acts as the brain of the computer. In gaming, it handles all the underlying game logic, artificial intelligence, physics calculations, and tells the GPU what to render.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Crosshair placement</h3>
        <p>The fundamental practice of keeping your aiming reticle consistently at head-height and anticipating exactly where an enemy might peek or appear. Good crosshair placement minimizes the physical distance the player needs to move their mouse when an engagement starts, significantly reducing reaction time.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>CS (Creep Score)</h3>
        <p>The total number of AI-controlled minions or neutral monsters a player has successfully delivered the killing blow to. High CS is crucial because it is the primary source of gold and experience.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Dedicated server</h3>
        <p>A robust, standalone server provided by the game's developer that handles all game logic and networking. Dedicated servers offer a significantly more stable, fair, and high-performance experience compared to P2P connections.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Desync</h3>
        <p>A total synchronization failure where what one player sees on their screen completely differs from what another player sees, or what the server believes is actually happening. This leads to players dying behind cover or shots seemingly phasing through targets.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>DLSS / FSR</h3>
        <p>Deep Learning Super Sampling (NVIDIA) and FidelityFX Super Resolution (AMD). Advanced AI and spatial upscaling technologies that render the game at a lower resolution to massively boost frame rates, then intelligently upscale the image to look almost indistinguishable from native resolution.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>DMCA (Digital Millennium Copyright Act)</h3>
        <p>Copyright law that affects streamers. Playing copyrighted music or showing copyrighted video without permission can result in the stream being muted, the VOD being deleted, or the channel being permanently banned.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Donation</h3>
        <p>A direct, one-time financial tip given by a viewer to a streamer, often accompanied by a text-to-speech message that is read aloud on the broadcast.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Draft</h3>
        <p>The critical pre-game phase where the two teams take turns strategically selecting the champions they will play and banning champions they do not want the enemy to play.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Drafting</h3>
        <p>The incredibly complex and highly strategic pre-game phase in MOBA titles where coaches and players take turns selecting their own champions and banning specific champions away from the enemy, aiming to build a superior team composition.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Drop shot</h3>
        <p>The tactic of instantly going prone (laying flat on the ground) while simultaneously shooting at an opponent in a close-quarters engagement, causing the enemy to miss their head or body shots.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Eco round</h3>
        <p>A round where a team deliberately chooses not to spend their in-game currency on expensive weapons and armor, saving their money to ensure they can afford a full loadout in the subsequent round.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>ELO</h3>
        <p>A rating system originally invented for chess by Arpad Elo, used to calculate the relative skill levels of players in competitive games. Beating a higher-rated player yields more points than beating a lower-rated one.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Emergent gameplay</h3>
        <p>Incredibly complex, unscripted, and entirely unique situations that arise organically as a result of the player interacting creatively with the game's physics, systems, and AI, often leading to solutions the developers never explicitly planned for.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Emotes</h3>
        <p>Custom, channel-specific emojis used extensively in Twitch and YouTube chat to react to the stream. Emotes like 'Kappa', 'PogChamp', and 'LUL' form the core vocabulary of streaming culture.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Engage</h3>
        <p>The act of initiating a team fight. Champions with strong engage tools usually have large area-of-effect crowd control abilities that can catch multiple enemies off guard.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Entry fragger</h3>
        <p>The role of the first player on a team to enter a contested area or bomb site. Their primary job is to get the first kill or gather crucial information, even if they die in the process.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Esports Organization (Org)</h3>
        <p>A massive, corporate business entity that fields multiple teams across various different gaming titles. Orgs are responsible for securing huge sponsorships, selling merchandise, and paying the lucrative salaries of their contracted players.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Extrapolation</h3>
        <p>When the client stops receiving updates from the server (due to lag or packet loss), it attempts to predict where an enemy will move based on their last known velocity. If the enemy changes direction during this time, extrapolation causes them to suddenly warp when the connection resumes.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>F (Press F to Pay Respects)</h3>
        <p>A widespread internet meme originating from Call of Duty: Advanced Warfare. Viewers flood the chat with the letter 'F' to jokingly express condolences when the streamer fails, dies in-game, or encounters bad luck.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Feed</h3>
        <p>To die repeatedly to the enemy team, granting them a massive advantage in gold and experience. A player who is 'fed' is extremely strong and difficult to defeat.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Flick</h3>
        <p>An extremely fast, reactive mouse movement used to quickly acquire and shoot a target that suddenly appears on the screen. Flicks rely heavily on muscle memory rather than conscious tracking.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Form factor</h3>
        <p>The physical size and standard layout of a motherboard and PC case. The most common sizes, from largest to smallest, are ATX, Micro-ATX (mATX), and Mini-ITX. The form factor dictates how many expansion slots and features are available.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Frag</h3>
        <p>Another term for a kill. The player with the most kills on a team is often referred to as the 'top fragger'.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Frame rate (FPS)</h3>
        <p>Frames Per Second. The frequency at which consecutive images (frames) are rendered by the GPU and displayed on the monitor. Higher frame rates result in noticeably smoother and far more responsive gameplay.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Franchise</h3>
        <p>A rigid, highly structured professional league model where organizations purchase permanent slots, eliminating the risk of relegation. This model mimics traditional sports leagues like the NBA, ensuring massive financial stability, revenue sharing, and sponsor confidence.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Freeze</h3>
        <p>A specific wave management technique where a player keeps the minion wave perfectly balanced in a favorable position, usually near their own tower, to farm safely and force the enemy to overextend.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>G-Sync / FreeSync</h3>
        <p>Adaptive sync technologies developed by NVIDIA and AMD, respectively. They synchronize the monitor's refresh rate dynamically with the GPU's fluctuating frame rate output, eliminating screen tearing entirely without introducing the heavy input lag associated with Vsync.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Gacha</h3>
        <p>A highly lucrative monetization mechanic implemented heavily in mobile games where players spend real-world money for a random chance to 'pull' or unlock powerful virtual characters or rare items, heavily mimicking the psychological mechanisms of gambling.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Game sense</h3>
        <p>A player's overarching, intuitive understanding of the game's flow. It involves anticipating enemy movements, predicting plays, understanding timings, and knowing when to take risks or play defensively.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Gank</h3>
        <p>A surprise attack or ambush on an enemy player, usually involving numerical superiority. Ganks are often executed by the Jungler or a rotating Mid laner to secure a kill and gain a lane advantage.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>GPU (Graphics Processing Unit)</h3>
        <p>The graphics card. It is the most critical component for gaming performance, entirely responsible for rendering the high-resolution images, complex textures, lighting, and 3D graphics you see on your monitor.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Griefing</h3>
        <p>The act of intentionally and maliciously sabotaging your own teammates and the game itself, such as destroying friendly structures, stealing resources, or purposefully feeding the enemy team.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Group stage</h3>
        <p>The grueling initial phase of a large tournament. Teams are divided into groups and play a round-robin format against each other to determine seeding and decide which top teams advance to the high-stakes playoff bracket.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Hardstuck</h3>
        <p>A player who has played a massive number of ranked matches but remains entirely unable to progress past their current rank, implying they have reached their absolute skill ceiling.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Hip fire</h3>
        <p>Shooting a weapon without aiming down the sights. It is generally less accurate but allows for faster movement and better peripheral vision in close-quarters combat.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Hit registration (Hitreg)</h3>
        <p>The underlying system that determines whether a bullet or attack successfully collided with an opponent. Poor netcode or high packet loss leads to 'bad hitreg', where a player clearly sees their bullet hit, but the server ignores the damage.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Hitscan</h3>
        <p>A type of weapon mechanic where the projectile instantly hits whatever is in the center of the crosshair the moment the trigger is pulled, with absolutely no travel time or bullet drop to account for.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Hitscan</h3>
        <p>A fundamental weapon programming mechanic where the projectile instantly strikes whatever is directly in the center of the crosshair the exact microsecond the trigger is pulled, completely ignoring travel time, wind resistance, or gravity.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Host</h3>
        <p>Similar to a raid, but instead of moving viewers to a new channel, the streamer embeds another creator's live video directly on their own channel page while they are offline.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>i-frames (Invincibility Frames)</h3>
        <p>A brief, specific window of animation frames during a dodge roll, dash, or special attack where the player character becomes completely immune to all incoming damage and status effects, allowing them to pass safely through enemy attacks.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>I/O Shield</h3>
        <p>The small, often frustrating metal plate installed in the back of the PC case that covers the gaps around the motherboard's external ports (USB, audio, ethernet) to protect against dust and electromagnetic interference.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>IGL (In-Game Leader)</h3>
        <p>The most crucial role in a tactical shooter team. The IGL acts as the field commander, analyzing the enemy's economy and positioning on the fly, and making split-second, highly strategic calls that dictate exactly how the team executes their round.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Interpolation</h3>
        <p>A visual smoothing technique used by the client. Since the client only receives updates from the server a certain number of times per second, it mathematically guesses and renders the movement of enemy players between those updates to prevent them from looking choppy.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Itemization</h3>
        <p>The strategic decision-making process of selecting and purchasing items during a match. Good itemization requires adapting your build to counter the specific damage types and abilities of the enemy team.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Jiggle peek</h3>
        <p>Briefly stepping out from behind cover and immediately stepping back in to safely gain information on enemy positions or bait out sniper shots without fully committing to a fight.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Jitter</h3>
        <p>The variance or fluctuation in your ping over time. Even if your average ping is low, high jitter means your connection is unstable, leading to an incredibly inconsistent, frustrating, and stuttering gameplay experience.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Jungle</h3>
        <p>The sprawling, un-laned areas of the map situated between the main lanes, populated by neutral monster camps. The Jungler role roams this area to farm and secure buffs.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Just Chatting</h3>
        <p>A massively popular category on Twitch where streamers interact directly with their audience, watch videos, or tell stories, focusing entirely on personality and conversation rather than gameplay.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Kiting</h3>
        <p>Continuously moving away from an pursuing enemy while attacking them at the same time. This technique allows ranged characters to deal damage while maintaining a safe distance from melee threats.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Kiting</h3>
        <p>A combat tactic that involves continuously moving away from a pursuing enemy while simultaneously turning back to attack them. This allows ranged characters to inflict maximum damage while staying completely out of the enemy's melee reach.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Ladder</h3>
        <p>The overall ranking system or leaderboard in a competitive game. Players 'climb the ladder' by winning matches and increasing their MMR or ranked points to reach the top positions.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Lag compensation</h3>
        <p>A complex algorithmic system implemented by developers to ensure that players with slightly higher ping can still successfully hit targets. It essentially 'rewinds' time on the server to check if a shot was valid based on the shooter's perspective at the exact moment they fired.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>LAN (Local Area Network)</h3>
        <p>The pinnacle of esports competition. Tournaments are played in massive arenas on a local network rather than over the public internet. This provides near-zero latency, absolute competitive fairness, and a massive live audience environment.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Lane</h3>
        <p>The specific, defined paths on a MOBA map where waves of AI-controlled minions travel and defensive towers are located. There are typically three main lanes: Top, Middle (Mid), and Bottom (Bot).</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Latency</h3>
        <p>A general term used interchangeably with ping. It refers to the physical delay in data transmission caused by the geographical distance between the player and the server, as well as the routing quality of the Internet Service Provider.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Leash</h3>
        <p>When laners help the Jungler defeat their first monster camp by dealing some initial damage before heading to their own lanes, speeding up the Jungler's early clear without stealing the kill or experience.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Ludonarrative dissonance</h3>
        <p>A term used in game critique describing the jarring disconnect that occurs when a game's narrative heavily contradicts its actual gameplay. For example, a cutscene portraying the hero as a pacifist, followed by gameplay where they mercilessly gun down hundreds of enemies.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Lurker</h3>
        <p>A viewer who actively watches the stream but rarely, if ever, types or participates in the chat. Lurkers represent the vast majority of a streamer's total viewership and are highly valued.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Macro</h3>
        <p>The overarching, grand strategy of the game, including map awareness, objective prioritization, rotation timing, and wave management. It contrasts with 'micro', which focuses on individual champion mechanics.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Macro</h3>
        <p>The overarching, grand strategic view of an entire match. Teams with superior macro execute flawless map rotations, secure critical neutral objectives with perfect timing, and manage the economy perfectly, completely suffocating the enemy team.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Major / Minor</h3>
        <p>The classification tiers of esports tournaments. Majors are the absolute highest-prestige, developer-sponsored events with massive prize pools and global importance, while Minors serve as the highly competitive qualifiers leading up to them.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Matchmaking region</h3>
        <p>The specific geographical cluster of servers a player connects to. To maintain competitive integrity and low ping, games attempt to group players within the same physical region, such as US-East, EU-West, or Asia.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Mechanics</h3>
        <p>The raw, physical skill required to execute actions in a game. Good mechanics encompass precise aiming, rapid and accurate clicking, and flawless execution of complex button combinations or ability combos.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Meta (Most Effective Tactic Available)</h3>
        <p>The currently dominant and widely accepted optimal strategies, character picks, or item builds in a game. The meta is constantly shifting due to developer balance updates and player discoveries.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Meta shift</h3>
        <p>A sudden, drastic change in the competitive landscape, usually caused by a major developer balance patch. It forces professional teams to entirely abandon their practiced strategies and rapidly adapt to newly powerful characters or items.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Metroidvania</h3>
        <p>A popular subgenre of action-adventure games focused heavily on non-linear exploration within a massive, interconnected world. Progress is inherently blocked by specific environmental obstacles that can only be bypassed by finding specialized items or abilities later in the game.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Micro</h3>
        <p>The individual, mechanical skill of a player. This includes precise clicking, ability targeting, dodging enemy skillshots, and executing complex champion combos.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Micro</h3>
        <p>The intense, localized mechanical skill of a single player. Exceptional micro involves executing completely flawless, lightning-fast ability combos, perfect crosshair tracking, and mathematically precise movement in the heat of a chaotic fight.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Mid</h3>
        <p>The middle lane of the map. Mid laners are typically mages or assassins who benefit from solo experience and have the central map positioning to easily roam and influence other lanes.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Min-maxing</h3>
        <p>The intense process of mathematically analyzing a game's systems to completely minimize a character's weaknesses and absolutely maximize their strengths, often resulting in highly specialized and uncompromising builds.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>MMR (Matchmaking Rating)</h3>
        <p>A hidden numerical value used by a game's matchmaking algorithm to pair players of roughly equal skill against each other to ensure fair and competitive matches. It is often separate from a player's visible rank.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Mod (Moderator)</h3>
        <p>Trusted members of the community appointed by the streamer to police the chat. Mods have the power to delete inappropriate messages, issue temporary timeouts, and permanently ban toxic users.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Motherboard</h3>
        <p>The main printed circuit board of the computer. It connects all the critical hardware components together—the CPU, GPU, RAM, and storage—allowing them to communicate and receive power from the power supply.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>MVP (Most Valuable Player)</h3>
        <p>The highly prestigious award given to the single player whose absolutely exceptional performance had the most massive, undeniable impact on their team's ultimate success throughout the entire duration of a tournament.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>NAT type</h3>
        <p>Network Address Translation type (Open, Moderate, or Strict). It determines how easily your console or PC can establish direct peer-to-peer connections with other players. A Strict NAT often prevents players from joining parties or voice chats.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Nerf</h3>
        <p>A balance change implemented by the developers in a patch that reduces the power, effectiveness, or stats of a specific character, item, or strategy that was deemed too strong for the health of the game.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Netcode</h3>
        <p>The broad umbrella term encompassing the entire networking infrastructure, programming, and synchronization techniques a specific game uses to ensure that the game state is consistent for all connected players, despite their varying latencies.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>NVMe</h3>
        <p>Non-Volatile Memory Express. An interface protocol specifically built for incredibly fast solid-state drives that connect directly to the motherboard via PCIe slots, offering speeds vastly superior to older SATA SSDs.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Objective control</h3>
        <p>The prioritization and securing of highly contested neutral monsters (like Dragons or Baron Nashor) or structures that provide significant, permanent, or temporary team-wide buffs and gold advantages.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>OBS (Open Broadcaster Software)</h3>
        <p>The industry-standard, free, and open-source software used by the vast majority of streamers to capture gameplay, configure audio sources, manage visual overlays, and encode the video for broadcast to platforms like Twitch or YouTube.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>One-tap</h3>
        <p>Killing an enemy with a single, perfectly placed bullet to the head. This term is heavily used in tactical shooters like Counter-Strike and Valorant.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>OP (Overpowered)</h3>
        <p>A character, weapon, or strategy that is currently far too strong compared to everything else in the game, completely dominating the meta and heavily skewing the balance of matches.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Overclocking</h3>
        <p>The advanced process of manually forcing a CPU, GPU, or RAM to run at a higher clock speed than the manufacturer's official specifications, increasing performance but also significantly increasing heat generation and power consumption.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Overlay</h3>
        <p>The customized graphical elements placed on top of the raw gameplay video, including webcam borders, social media handles, recent subscriber lists, and sponsor logos, designed to give the stream a professional look.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Packet loss</h3>
        <p>A severe networking issue that occurs when data packets traveling between your network and the game server simply fail to arrive at their destination. This results in registered hits not counting, players teleporting, or complete disconnections.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>PCIe (Peripheral Component Interconnect Express)</h3>
        <p>The high-speed interface standard used for connecting the graphics card, NVMe SSDs, and other expansion cards directly to the motherboard.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Peeker's advantage</h3>
        <p>A networking phenomenon in online shooters where the player actively moving around a corner sees the holding player slightly before the holding player sees them on their screen. This is due to the slight delay in data traveling from the server to the defending player's client.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Peel</h3>
        <p>The act of using crowd control abilities, positioning, or damage to force enemy attackers away from a vulnerable, high-value teammate, typically the ADC or Mid laner.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Peer-to-Peer (P2P)</h3>
        <p>A networking model where one of the actual players acts as the 'host' server for the match, rather than relying on a dedicated server provided by the developer. This gives the host a massive ping advantage and ends the game if they disconnect.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Ping</h3>
        <p>Also known as latency, this is the round-trip time, measured in milliseconds (ms), that it takes for a data packet to travel from your gaming PC to the game server and back. Lower ping means a more responsive game.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Poggers</h3>
        <p>A highly popular emote and slang term used to express extreme excitement, hype, or genuine amazement at a highly skilled play or a surprising, positive event on stream.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Port forwarding</h3>
        <p>A manual configuration made in a router's settings to open specific network ports, allowing direct incoming connections. This is often necessary to achieve an Open NAT type or to host private game servers from home.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Power creep</h3>
        <p>The gradual, inevitable process in long-running live-service games where newly introduced characters, weapons, or abilities are inherently stronger than older ones, rendering the original content completely obsolete and forcing players to constantly acquire the new items to stay competitive.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Pre-fire</h3>
        <p>Firing a weapon at a common hiding spot or corner just before or exactly as you peek it, anticipating that an enemy is there. If an enemy is present, they take damage instantly before they can react.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Prize pool</h3>
        <p>The total accumulated amount of prize money distributed among the winning teams at the conclusion of a tournament. Major events like The International boast prize pools well into the tens of millions of dollars, largely funded by the community.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Proc-gen (Procedural Generation)</h3>
        <p>An advanced method of creating vast amounts of game data, levels, or terrain algorithmically on the fly rather than developing them manually. This allows games like Minecraft to have virtually infinite, totally unique worlds.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Projectile</h3>
        <p>A weapon mechanic where the bullet or rocket has actual travel time and often physical drop over distance. Players must 'lead' their shots, aiming ahead of a moving target to ensure the projectile connects.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Projectile</h3>
        <p>A weapon mechanic that models the physics of a bullet or energy blast, incorporating actual travel time and often arcing due to simulated gravity. This forces players to calculate speed and aim ahead of moving targets.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>PSU (Power Supply Unit)</h3>
        <p>The component that converts power from the wall outlet into usable power for the internal PC parts. A high-quality PSU with enough wattage is essential for system stability and preventing sudden shutdowns during intense gaming.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>QoS (Quality of Service)</h3>
        <p>A highly useful feature found in modern routers that allows users to prioritize specific types of network traffic. Gamers can use QoS to prioritize their gaming PC or console, ensuring their connection remains stable even if the network is busy.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>QTE (Quick Time Event)</h3>
        <p>A heavily scripted, cinematic gameplay sequence where the player must press a specific button or sequence of buttons exactly as they flash on the screen to avoid failing the scene or dying, often criticized for limiting actual player control.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Quality of Life (QoL)</h3>
        <p>Small but highly impactful updates, adjustments, or UI improvements made by developers to make playing the game significantly smoother, less tedious, and more enjoyable without fundamentally altering the core mechanics or balance.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Raid</h3>
        <p>A feature where a streamer, upon ending their broadcast, automatically redirects all of their current viewers to another streamer's channel. It is a powerful way to network, show support, and help smaller creators grow.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>RAM (Random Access Memory)</h3>
        <p>Extremely fast, volatile short-term memory that the CPU uses to temporarily store the data it is actively working on. Having enough RAM ensures games run smoothly without stuttering as new assets are loaded.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Ranked</h3>
        <p>A competitive game mode where players are matched based on skill and gain or lose rating points based on the outcome of the match, progressing through distinct tiers (e.g., Bronze, Silver, Gold, Platinum, Diamond).</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Ray tracing</h3>
        <p>An extremely demanding advanced rendering technique that physically simulates the realistic behavior of light, creating incredibly lifelike reflections, shadows, and global illumination, requiring specialized hardware found in modern high-end GPUs.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Refresh rate</h3>
        <p>Measured in Hertz (Hz), it is the maximum number of times per second a monitor can draw a new image. A 144Hz monitor can display up to 144 frames per second, providing a massive advantage in fast-paced games over standard 60Hz displays.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Resolution</h3>
        <p>The total number of pixels displayed on a screen, dictating image sharpness. Common resolutions include 1080p (Full HD), 1440p (QHD), and 2160p (4K). Higher resolutions require significantly more GPU power to run smoothly.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>RNG (Random Number Generation)</h3>
        <p>The underlying algorithms used by games to determine unpredictable events, such as critical hit chances, loot drops, or spawn locations. High RNG can reduce the impact of pure skill in competitive scenarios.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>RNG (Random Number Generation)</h3>
        <p>The core algorithm used by games to determine unpredictable events. It governs everything from whether an RPG attack results in a critical hit, to the specific rarity of loot dropped by a boss, ensuring no two playthroughs are exactly identical.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Roguelike</h3>
        <p>A punishing subgenre of games heavily defined by randomly generated levels, turn-based combat, and permanent death. When a player dies, they lose all progress, items, and levels, starting the entire game completely over from scratch.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Roguelite</h3>
        <p>A more forgiving spin-off of the Roguelike genre. While it retains procedurally generated runs and permadeath, it introduces persistent meta-progression, allowing players to unlock permanent upgrades, weapons, or stats that carry over between their attempts.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Rollback</h3>
        <p>An advanced networking technique predominantly used in fighting games. It instantaneously predicts a player's inputs to eliminate perceived latency, and if the prediction is wrong upon receiving the actual data, it invisibly 'rolls back' the game state to correct it.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Roster</h3>
        <p>The official, finalized lineup of players actively contracted to compete for an esports organization. Managing a roster involves scouting talent, handling player buyouts, and finding the perfect synergy between vastly different player personalities.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Roster lock</h3>
        <p>The strict, officially enforced deadline set by tournament organizers. After this exact date, teams are completely forbidden from making any further changes to their player lineup for the remainder of the competitive season.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Rotation</h3>
        <p>The tactical act of moving from one area of the map to another, typically to support teammates under attack, defend a different bomb site, or flank enemies. Fast and unpredictable rotations are key to confusing the opposing team and maintaining map control.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Routing</h3>
        <p>The specific physical path your data packets take through various internet nodes to reach the game server. Bad routing by an ISP can cause a player to experience high ping even if the server is geographically very close to them.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Rubberbanding</h3>
        <p>A highly frustrating visual effect caused by extreme packet loss or high latency. The player appears to move forward on their screen, but the server rejects the movement, violently teleporting the player back to their previous position like a snapping rubber band.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Rubberbanding (AI)</h3>
        <p>A highly controversial design mechanic used primarily in racing games to maintain tension. The AI opponents are artificially programmed to gain impossible speed boosts when trailing far behind, or drastically slow down when far ahead, ensuring the race is always close regardless of player skill.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Sandbox</h3>
        <p>A game genre or mode that drops the player into a simulated world with no strict, overarching goals or linear narrative, providing them with a massive suite of tools to create their own fun, alter the environment, and experiment freely.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Save scumming</h3>
        <p>The controversial player tactic of heavily abusing a game's manual save or quicksave feature by reloading the save file repeatedly until they achieve a perfect outcome in a fight, conversation, or RNG-based event.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Screen tearing</h3>
        <p>A distracting visual artifact that occurs when the GPU pushes out frames significantly faster or slower than the monitor's refresh rate, resulting in multiple frames being displayed on screen simultaneously, creating horizontal 'tears' in the image.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Scrim</h3>
        <p>An abbreviation for scrimmage. A highly organized, private practice match played between two competitive or professional teams to test strategies and improve coordination without the pressure of an official tournament.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Server-side</h3>
        <p>Calculations and validations that occur strictly on the game's authoritative server. This ensures competitive integrity and prevents cheating, as the server always has the final say on movement, damage, and hit registration.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Shotcaller</h3>
        <p>The designated player on a team responsible for making the final macro decisions, dictating rotations, calling out targets in team fights, and managing the team's overall strategy during a match.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Skill tree</h3>
        <p>A branching, visual progression system that allows players to heavily customize their character's abilities, passive stats, and combat style by investing experience points earned through leveling up into specific, mutually exclusive paths.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Skillshot</h3>
        <p>An ability that requires the player to manually aim a projectile or area of effect, meaning it can miss or be dodged by the enemy, as opposed to a targeted ability that automatically hits.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Smokes</h3>
        <p>Utility grenades or abilities that deploy a cloud of smoke, blocking line of sight. They are crucial for executing strategies, crossing open areas safely, or delaying enemy pushes.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Smokescreen</h3>
        <p>A deceptive, psychological strategy utilized during the drafting phase. A team deliberately picks specific characters early to trick the opposing team into believing they are running one strategy, before completely pivoting their composition with their final picks.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Smurfing</h3>
        <p>The highly frowned-upon practice of an experienced, high-ranked player creating a brand new or artificially low-ranked account specifically to play against and easily dominate less skilled opponents.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Snowball</h3>
        <p>A situation where a small early advantage (like a single kill or CS lead) is leveraged to gain progressively larger advantages, eventually becoming an unstoppable force that easily wins the game.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Souls-like</h3>
        <p>A notoriously challenging subgenre of action RPGs inspired by Dark Souls. Key features include high-stakes combat, environmental storytelling, checkpoint systems that respawn all enemies when rested at, and a harsh mechanic where players drop their accumulated currency upon death.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Spawn trap</h3>
        <p>A situation where one team gains such overwhelming map control that they can continuously kill the opposing team immediately as they respawn in their base, preventing them from playing the game.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Split push</h3>
        <p>A macro strategy where one player, usually a strong duelist, pushes a lane on the opposite side of the map from their team to apply pressure and force the enemy to divide their attention and resources.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Spray pattern</h3>
        <p>The predictable and specific path that bullets follow when a player fires a weapon continuously in fully automatic mode. Players must learn to pull their mouse in the opposite direction of the pattern to maintain accuracy, a skill known as spray control.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>SSD (Solid State Drive)</h3>
        <p>A storage device that uses flash memory, offering exponentially faster read and write speeds than traditional mechanical hard drives (HDDs). An SSD drastically reduces game load times and eliminates texture pop-in.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Stand-in</h3>
        <p>A substitute player temporarily brought in to compete in an official match when a member of the primary roster is unavailable due to sudden illness, visa issues, or internal team disputes, often with very little time to practice with the team.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Strafe</h3>
        <p>Moving sideways (left or right) to dodge enemy fire while keeping the camera focused forward on the target. In many tactical shooters, players must completely stop strafing to regain weapon accuracy before firing.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Stream deck</h3>
        <p>A popular physical macro pad with customizable LCD keys, allowing streamers to easily switch scenes, trigger sound effects, or mute their microphone with a single button press without minimizing their game.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Stream sniping</h3>
        <p>The highly toxic and often bannable practice of a viewer maliciously watching a streamer's live broadcast to discover their in-game location and queue into their match with the sole intent of killing them or ruining their game.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Sub (Subscriber)</h3>
        <p>A viewer who pays a recurring monthly fee (or uses a free Prime subscription) to financially support a streamer. In return, they typically receive ad-free viewing, custom emotes, and a special badge next to their name in chat.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Support</h3>
        <p>A role dedicated to assisting and protecting the team, particularly the ADC in the early game. Supports focus on providing utility, crowd control, healing, and map vision rather than dealing damage or taking CS.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>TCP/UDP</h3>
        <p>The two primary protocols used for transmitting data. TCP guarantees delivery but is slow, making it bad for gaming. UDP is fast and does not check for lost packets, making it the absolute standard for responsive online multiplayer games.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Telegraphing</h3>
        <p>A crucial principle of fair game design where an enemy performs a highly visible, distinct animation or auditory cue significantly before launching a devastating attack, giving the observant player a fair window of opportunity to react and dodge.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Thermal throttle</h3>
        <p>A built-in safety mechanism where a CPU or GPU automatically and drastically lowers its clock speed and performance to reduce heat output and prevent catastrophic physical damage when operating temperatures get dangerously high.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Throw</h3>
        <p>When a professional team possesses a massive, almost guaranteed lead in gold or map control, but commits a completely catastrophic error or engages in a terrible team fight, resulting in them losing a game they absolutely should have won.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Throwing</h3>
        <p>Intentionally or accidentally making a series of catastrophic mistakes that costs your team a match they were otherwise heavily favored to win, squandering a significant lead.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Tick rate</h3>
        <p>The precise frequency, measured in Hertz (Hz), at which the central game server updates the current game state and processes player inputs. A 128Hz server provides a much more precise and competitive experience than a standard 64Hz server.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Tier list</h3>
        <p>A subjective but widely referenced ranking system that categorizes characters, weapons, or strategies from best (S-Tier) to worst (F-Tier) based on their current viability in the competitive meta.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Tilt</h3>
        <p>A state of deep emotional frustration, anger, or loss of focus caused by consecutive losses, mistakes, or toxic behavior, which severely and negatively impacts a player's decision-making and gameplay performance.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Timeout</h3>
        <p>A temporary restriction placed on a viewer by a moderator, preventing them from sending messages in chat for a set duration, usually as a warning for breaking channel rules.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Tower dive</h3>
        <p>The risky, coordinated maneuver of attacking an enemy player while they are under the protection of their own defensive tower. The tower will attack the aggressors, making the timing and execution crucial.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Toxic</h3>
        <p>Behavior that ruins the experience for others, including verbal abuse, griefing, intentionally feeding, or generally creating a hostile and negative environment within the game.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Tryhard</h3>
        <p>A somewhat derogatory term used by casual players to describe someone who is putting an excessive, almost desperate amount of effort into winning, often prioritizing victory over having fun.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>TTK (Time to Kill)</h3>
        <p>The average amount of time it takes to eliminate an opponent using a specific weapon or ability. Games like Valorant have a very low TTK, meaning players die almost instantly, whereas games like Apex Legends have a high TTK, requiring sustained tracking and movement.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Vertical slice</h3>
        <p>A fully playable, highly polished demonstration version of a game that showcases all of its core features, graphics, and mechanics working perfectly together in a single, short level, often used internally to pitch the game to publishers for funding.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Vision control</h3>
        <p>The battle for information on the map, achieved by strategically placing wards to see enemy movements and clearing enemy wards to deny them information and set up ambushes.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>VOD (Video On Demand)</h3>
        <p>A recorded, archived version of a past live stream that viewers can watch at their own convenience. VODs are crucial for building an audience who cannot always tune in live.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>VOD review</h3>
        <p>The practice of watching recorded videos (VODs) of your own past matches, or those of professional players, to deeply analyze mistakes, study enemy tendencies, and identify areas for improvement.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>VRM (Voltage Regulator Module)</h3>
        <p>Crucial components on the motherboard and graphics card that ensure the CPU and GPU receive a steady, clean, and exact amount of voltage. High-quality VRMs are essential for stable overclocking.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Vsync (Vertical Sync)</h3>
        <p>A display technology that artificially limits the game's frame rate to exactly match the monitor's refresh rate. While it eliminates screen tearing, it often introduces noticeable input lag, making it unfavorable for competitive gaming.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>VTuber</h3>
        <p>A Virtual YouTuber or streamer who uses a highly animated, motion-captured 2D or 3D digital avatar instead of a traditional facecam to represent themselves on stream.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Wallbang</h3>
        <p>Shooting an enemy through a penetrable surface, such as a thin wall, wooden door, or crate. Different weapons usually have different levels of penetration power.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Wave management</h3>
        <p>The advanced skill of manipulating the behavior of minion waves (freezing, pushing, or slow pushing) to deny the enemy gold and experience, or to create opportunities to back to base or roam.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
